{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CAWxo8Sf8xbe5gjb2wagVu","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 29 — Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** Draft\n     4→**Date:** 2026-03-17\n     5→**Based on:** Iteration 28 feedback (11 failures, all generated files)\n     6→\n     7→## Overview\n     8→\n     9→Iteration 28 implemented all 4 fixes from the iteration 27 plan (blind OCR repair, direct-successor bonus, multi-line dedup protection, spillover threshold lowering). The score held at 90.1% — the same 11 failures persist. By reading the actual test files and tracing through the code, this plan identifies why each fix failed and proposes corrected approaches.\n    10→\n    11→## Problem Statement\n    12→\n    13→The iteration 27 plan correctly identified the 4 failure patterns but the implementations had bugs or gaps:\n    14→\n    15→1. **Blind OCR repair maps `1→l` instead of `1→i`** — The mixed-case path in `applyBlindOcrRepair` always substitutes `l`, producing garbled text like `Bralsed Cod wlth Whlte Wlne` instead of `Braised Cod with White Wine`.\n    16→2. **Direct-successor bonus ignores blank lines** — The bonus checks `lines[position - 1]`, but in both the Halibut and Ogórkowa Zupa files, there's a blank line between the header and the title. The bonus never fires.\n    17→3. **English food categories not treated as section labels** — `VEGETABLES` and `FISH & SEAFOOD` pass hard filters because only Polish food categories (warzywa, ryby, etc.) are in `SECTION_LABELS`. English equivalents (vegetables, fish, seafood) are only in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`, which `passesHardFilters` doesn't check.\n    18→4. **Overflow marker regex doesn't match actual test marker** — `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]` fails to match the regex `PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\s+(OVERFLOW|CONTENT)` because the text says `PREVIOUS PAGE` followed by `- PARTIAL RECIPE`, not `OVERFLOW` or `CONTENT`.\n    19→5. **`findBurstEnd` misses non-consecutive instruction prologues** — The Mushroom Risotto file alternates cooking instructions (`Reduce heat...`, `Season with...`) with prose (`creamy but still al dente...`), breaking the consecutive-instruction count at j=1.\n    20→\n    21→## Goals\n    22→\n    23→- Fix the root causes identified above, not just increase bonuses or thresholds\n    24→- Fix all 11 failures without regressing existing passing tests\n    25→- Keep changes targeted — the architecture works, the edge-case handling has specific bugs\n    26→\n    27→## Non-Goals\n    28→\n    29→- Replacing the embedding-based approach\n    30→- Reducing overall code complexity\n    31→- Handling new patterns not seen in iterations 27-28\n    32→\n    33→---\n    34→\n    35→## Fix 1: Dual-variant blind OCR repair (5 cases + 1 case)\n    36→\n    37→**Affects:** Braised Cod with White Wine, Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami, Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip, Żurek Krakowski, Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi\n    38→\n    39→### Root Cause\n    40→\n    41→`applyBlindOcrRepair` in mixed-case mode has:\n    42→```typescript\n    43→.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])1/g, \"l\")\n    44→.replace(/1(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"l\")\n    45→```\n    46→\n    47→This always maps `1→l`. For recipe text, `1→i` is correct far more often:\n    48→- `Bra1sed` → should be `Braised` (i), not `Bralsed` (l)\n    49→- `w1th` → should be `with` (i), not `wlth` (l)\n    50→- `Wh1te` → should be `White` (i), not `Whlte` (l)\n    51→- `W1ne` → should be `Wine` (i), not `Wlne` (l)\n    52→- `Sern1k` → should be `Sernik` (i), not `Sernlk` (l)\n    53→\n    54→The ALL_CAPS path (`1→I`) works because uppercase `I` and `L` are visually similar and `I` is the correct character for most recipe words. The mixed-case path needs the same correctness.\n    55→\n    56→Additionally, `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi` has erratic casing (`KoPyTka`) that doesn't trigger the ALL_CAPS path and confuses the mixed-case repair.\n    57→\n    58→### Fix\n    59→\n    60→**Part A: Generate both `i` and `l` variants as separate candidates.**\n    61→\n    62→Instead of choosing one substitution, generate two candidates — one with `1→i` and one with `1→l`. The embedding scorer will pick the one that embeds as a better title. This avoids needing to guess which letter is correct.\n    63→\n    64→```typescript\n    65→// In buildCandidates, replace the single blind-repair block with:\n    66→if (line.index <= 5 && OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text)) {\n    67→  const variants = generateBlindOcrVariants(singleText);\n    68→  for (const variant of variants) {\n    69→    if (variant !== singleText && passesHardFilters(variant)) {\n    70→      const norm = variant.toLowerCase();\n    71→      if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n    72→        seen.add(norm);\n    73→        candidates.push({ text: variant, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n    74→      }\n    75→    }\n    76→  }\n    77→}\n    78→```\n    79→\n    80→`generateBlindOcrVariants` returns an array of up to 2 variants:\n    81→1. `i`-variant: `1→i` between lowercase letters, `¡→i`, `€→e`\n    82→2. `l`-variant: `1→l` between lowercase letters (the current behavior)\n    83→\n    84→For ALL_CAPS text, only one variant (`1→I`) is needed (current behavior is correct).\n    85→\n    86→**Part B: Normalize erratic casing before repair.**\n    87→\n    88→For the Kopytka case (`KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi`), add a casing normalization step that detects erratic mixed-case (neither title-case nor ALL_CAPS) and normalizes to title-case before OCR repair. A line has \"erratic casing\" when individual words have uppercase letters in non-initial positions (like `KoPyTka` where `P`, `T`, `k` break the pattern).\n    89→\n    90→```typescript\n    91→function hasErraticCasing(text: string): boolean {\n    92→  return text.split(/\\s+/).some(word => {\n    93→    if (word.length < 3) return false;\n    94→    if (isAllCaps(word)) return false;\n    95→    // Check for uppercase letters after position 0 that aren't part of known patterns\n    96→    // (e.g., McDonald's is OK, KoPyTka is not)\n    97→    const inner = word.slice(1);\n    98→    const upperInner = (inner.match(/[A-ZÀ-Ż]/g) || []).length;\n    99→    const lowerInner = (inner.match(/[a-zà-ż]/g) || []).length;\n   100→    return upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3;\n   101→  });\n   102→}\n   103→\n   104→function normalizeErraticCasing(text: string): string {\n   105→  return text.split(/(\\s+)/).map(token => {\n   106→    if (/^\\s+$/.test(token)) return token;\n   107→    if (isAllCaps(token)) return token;\n   108→    if (hasErraticCasing(token)) {\n   109→      // Normalize to title-case: first letter upper, rest lower\n   110→      return token.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + token.slice(1).toLowerCase();\n   111→    }\n   112→    return token;\n   113→  }).join(\"\");\n   114→}\n   115→```\n   116→\n   117→Apply this normalization as a pre-step before blind OCR repair for early-position candidates:\n   118→\n   119→```typescript\n   120→if (line.index <= 5 && (OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text) || hasErraticCasing(line.text))) {\n   121→  let repairable = singleText;\n   122→  if (hasErraticCasing(repairable)) {\n   123→    repairable = normalizeErraticCasing(repairable);\n   124→  }\n   125→  const variants = generateBlindOcrVariants(repairable);\n   126→  // ... add variants as candidates\n   127→}\n   128→```\n   129→\n   130→**Why this works:**\n   131→- `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne` → `i`-variant: `Braised Cod with White Wine` (embeds perfectly as a title)\n   132→- `Drożdże Sern1k` → `i`-variant: `Drożdże Sernik` (correct)\n   133→- `KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi` → normalize: `Kopytka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi` → repair `¡→i`: `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi` (correct)\n   134→\n   135→**Risk:** Generating extra candidates costs one additional embedding computation per variant. With the limit of first 5 lines, this adds at most 5 extra candidates — well within the 25-candidate cap. The embedding scorer naturally rejects wrong variants (e.g., `l`-variant `Bralsed` will score poorly).\n   136→\n   137→---\n   138→\n   139→## Fix 2: Add English food categories to hard-filter section labels (3 cases)\n   140→\n   141→**Affects:** Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce, Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan, Ogórkowa Zupa (indirectly)\n   142→\n   143→### Root Cause\n   144→\n   145→`passesHardFilters` calls `isSectionLabel`, which checks `SECTION_LABELS`. Polish food categories (warzywa, mieso, ryby, zupy, etc.) are in `SECTION_LABELS` and get filtered. But their English equivalents are only in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`, which `passesHardFilters` doesn't check.\n   146→\n   147→Result: `VEGETABLES` (from the Roasted Asparagus file) passes hard filters and becomes a candidate with ALL_CAPS bonus. `FISH & SEAFOOD` (from the Halibut file) also passes.\n   148→\n   149→### Fix\n   150→\n   151→Add `isCategorySectionLabel` as a hard filter check:\n   152→\n   153→```typescript\n   154→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n   155→  // ... existing checks ...\n   156→  if (isSectionLabel(text)) return false;\n   157→  if (isCategorySectionLabel(text)) return false;  // NEW\n   158→  // ... rest of checks ...\n   159→}\n   160→```\n   161→\n   162→Also handle compound category headers like `FISH & SEAFOOD`:\n   163→\n   164→```typescript\n   165→// In passesHardFilters, after the isCategorySectionLabel check:\n   166→// Multi-word category headers: \"FISH & SEAFOOD\", \"MEAT & POULTRY\"\n   167→if (/ [&] /.test(text)) {\n   168→  const parts = text.split(/\\s*&\\s*/);\n   169→  if (parts.every(p => isCategorySectionLabel(p.trim()))) return false;\n   170→}\n   171→```\n   172→\n   173→This needs `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` to also include common header components: add `\"meat\"`, `\"fish & seafood\"`, `\"meat & poultry\"`.\n   174→\n   175→**Why this works:** `VEGETABLES` → `isCategorySectionLabel(\"vegetables\")` → true → filtered. `FISH & SEAFOOD` → split on `&` → `[\"FISH\", \"SEAFOOD\"]` → both in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` → filtered. The actual titles (`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce`, `Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan`) are multi-word recipe names that won't match category labels.\n   176→\n   177→**Risk:** Could filter a legitimate title that's a single food category word (e.g., a recipe literally called \"Vegetables\"). Mitigated by the fact that real recipe titles are almost always more specific (\"Roasted Vegetables\", \"Vegetable Stir Fry\"). Single-word category headers are section labels, not recipe titles.\n   178→\n   179→---\n   180→\n   181→## Fix 3: Direct-successor bonus should skip blank lines (2 cases)\n   182→\n   183→**Affects:** Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce, Ogórkowa Zupa\n   184→\n   185→### Root Cause\n   186→\n   187→The direct-successor bonus (added in iteration 28) checks `lines[candidate.position - 1]`. In both failing files, there's a blank line between the header and the title:\n   188→\n   189→```\n   190→FISH & SEAFOOD        ← header (line 0)\n   191→                      ← blank (line 1)\n   192→Halibut with ...      ← title (line 2), but lines[2-1] = blank\n   193→```\n   194→\n   195→```\n   196→Lato | Zupy | ...     ← metadata (line 0)\n   197→                      ← blank (line 1)\n   198→OGÓRKOWA ZUPA         ← title (line 2), but lines[2-1] = blank\n   199→```\n   200→\n   201→The bonus never fires because blank lines are not headers.\n   202→\n   203→### Fix\n   204→\n   205→Scan backward from the candidate to find the nearest non-empty line, instead of just checking position-1:\n   206→\n   207→```typescript\n   208→for (let ci = 0; ci < scored.length && ci <= 2; ci++) {\n   209→  const candidate = scored[ci];\n   210→  if (candidate.position > 0) {\n   211→    // Scan backward past blank lines to find nearest non-empty preceding line\n   212→    let prevPos = candidate.position - 1;\n   213→    while (prevPos >= 0 && lines[prevPos].trim() === \"\") {\n   214→      prevPos--;\n   215→    }\n   216→    if (prevPos >= 0) {\n   217→      const prevLine = lines[prevPos].trim();\n   218→      const prevIsHeader =\n   219→        isSectionLabel(prevLine) ||\n   220→        isCategorySectionLabel(prevLine) ||          // NEW: also check category labels\n   221→        looksLikeMetadata(prevLine) ||\n   222→        prevLine.includes(\" | \") ||\n   223→        (/ [&] /.test(prevLine) &&                   // NEW: compound category headers\n   224→         prevLine.split(/\\s*&\\s*/).every(p => isCategorySectionLabel(p.trim())));\n   225→      if (prevIsHeader) {\n   226→        candidate.score += 0.10;\n   227→        candidate.baseScore += 0.10;\n   228→        candidate.thresholdScore += 0.10;\n   229→      }\n   230→    }\n   231→  }\n   232→}\n   233→```\n   234→\n   235→Note: With Fix 2, `FISH & SEAFOOD` and `VEGETABLES` are now filtered by hard filters and won't be candidates. But they still exist as lines that the direct-successor bonus should detect. The bonus now also checks `isCategorySectionLabel` when scanning previous lines, so it recognizes `FISH & SEAFOOD` / `VEGETABLES` as headers even though they're filtered from candidacy.\n   236→\n   237→**Why this works:** For Halibut, the bonus scans back from position 2, skips blank line 1, finds `FISH & SEAFOOD` at position 0. Compound category check matches. Bonus fires.\n   238→\n   239→For Ogórkowa Zupa, scans back from position 2, skips blank line 1, finds `Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...` at position 0. `prevLine.includes(\" | \")` matches. Bonus fires.\n   240→\n   241→**Risk:** Scanning too far back could match a stale header. Mitigated by the existing `ci <= 2` guard (only top 3 candidates) and by requiring the previous non-empty line to actually be a header pattern.\n   242→\n   243→---\n   244→\n   245→## Fix 4: Broaden overflow marker detection (1 case)\n   246→\n   247→**Affects:** Peach Cobbler\n   248→\n   249→### Root Cause\n   250→\n   251→The file starts with `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]`. The `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` regex is:\n   252→```\n   253→/\\b(PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\s+(OVERFLOW|CONTENT)|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION|CORRUPTED\\s+SECTION)\\b/i\n   254→```\n   255→\n   256→This expects:\n   257→- `PREVIOUS RECIPE OVERFLOW` or `PREVIOUS PAGE OVERFLOW` or `PREVIOUS PAGE CONTENT`\n   258→- `SPILLOVER`\n   259→- `CONTINUATION`\n   260→- `CORRUPTED SECTION`\n   261→\n   262→The actual text has `CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE` — `CORRUPTED` is not followed by `SECTION`, and `PREVIOUS PAGE` is not followed by `OVERFLOW`/`CONTENT`.\n   263→\n   264→### Fix\n   265→\n   266→Broaden the regex to match more natural variations of corruption/spillover markers:\n   267→\n   268→```typescript\n   269→const OVERFLOW_MARKERS = /\\b(PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\b|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION|CORRUPTED\\s+(SECTION|TEXT)\\b|PARTIAL\\s+RECIPE)\\b/i;\n   270→```\n   271→\n   272→Changes:\n   273→- `PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)` — no longer requires `OVERFLOW`/`CONTENT` after it. Any mention of \"previous recipe\" or \"previous page\" is an overflow signal.\n   274→- `CORRUPTED\\s+(SECTION|TEXT)` — matches both `CORRUPTED SECTION` and `CORRUPTED TEXT`.\n   275→- `PARTIAL\\s+RECIPE` — matches the `PARTIAL RECIPE` marker directly.\n   276→\n   277→Also add a check for the common `[...]` bracket pattern used in generated files:\n   278→\n   279→```typescript\n   280→// Additional overflow detection: lines that are fully bracketed annotations\n   281→// like \"[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]\"\n   282→if (/^\\[.*\\b(PREVIOUS|CORRUPTED|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION)\\b.*\\]$/i.test(lines[k].text)) {\n   283→  // Treat as overflow marker — scan forward for boundary\n   284→  // ... same forward-scan logic as existing overflow handling\n   285→}\n   286→```\n   287→\n   288→**Why this works:** `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]` now matches via both `CORRUPTED\\s+TEXT` and `PARTIAL\\s+RECIPE` and the bracketed-annotation check. The forward scan finds the `---` separator at line 20 and sets `overflowEnd` to 21. `PEACH COBBLER` at line 22 is the first candidate after spillover.\n   289→\n   290→**Risk:** Broader matching could trigger on legitimate recipe text that happens to contain words like \"previous\" or \"partial\". Mitigated by requiring the match to be part of a marker phrase (word boundary `\\b` + multi-word patterns), not just a standalone word. The bracketed-annotation check is safe because `[...]` lines are already filtered by hard filters — this just ensures the spillover skip logic also catches them.\n   291→\n   292→---\n   293→\n   294→## Fix 5: Detect interleaved instruction/prose prologues (1 case)\n   295→\n   296→**Affects:** Mushroom Risotto\n   297→\n   298→### Root Cause\n   299→\n   300→The file starts with:\n   301→```\n   302→Reduce heat and stir in the remaining stock, one ladle at a time, until the rice is   ← cooking instruction (Reduce)\n   303→creamy but still al dente, about 18-20 minutes. The risotto should flow slightly...    ← prose continuation\n   304→Season with salt and white pepper. Finish with butter and grated Parmigiano-Reggiano.  ← cooking instruction (Season/Finish)\n   305→```\n   306→\n   307→`findBurstEnd`'s instruction-prologue check requires CONSECUTIVE lines matching `looksLikeCookingInstruction`. Line 0 matches (`Reduce`), but line 1 starts with `creamy` (lowercase, no cooking verb), breaking the streak at j=1. The threshold is j≥3, so no skip occurs.\n   308→\n   309→The prose-prologue check also fails: line 0 starts with uppercase `R`, which doesn't match the lowercase-start requirement.\n   310→\n   311→### Fix\n   312→\n   313→Replace the strict consecutive-instruction/prose checks with a unified \"body-content prologue\" detector that tolerates interleaving. The insight is that spillover text is a mix of instructions and prose — we should count EITHER type:\n   314→\n   315→```typescript\n   316→// In findBurstEnd, replace the separate instruction-prologue and prose-prologue checks with:\n   317→if (i === 0) {\n   318→  let j = 0;\n   319→  while (j < lines.length) {\n   320→    const t = lines[j].text;\n   321→    const isInstruction = looksLikeCookingInstruction(t);\n   322→    const isProse = (\n   323→      /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(t) ||\n   324→      t.endsWith(\",\") ||\n   325→      (t.endsWith(\".\") && wordCount(t) > 4)\n   326→    ) && wordCount(t) >= 4;\n   327→    // Also detect continuation lines: start lowercase or with a comma/conjunction\n   328→    const isContinuation = /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(t) && wordCount(t) >= 2;\n   329→\n   330→    if (isInstruction || isProse || isContinuation) {\n   331→      j++;\n   332→    } else {\n   333→      break;\n   334→    }\n   335→  }\n   336→  if (j >= 3) {\n   337→    i = j;\n   338→  }\n   339→}\n   340→```\n   341→\n   342→The key change: instructions and prose lines are counted together. A cooking instruction followed by a prose continuation followed by another instruction all count toward the threshold.\n   343→\n   344→**Why this works:** For Mushroom Risotto:\n   345→- Line 0: `Reduce heat and stir...` → `looksLikeCookingInstruction` matches → j=1\n   346→- Line 1: `creamy but still al dente...` → starts lowercase, 4+ words → `isContinuation` matches → j=2\n   347→- Line 2: `Season with salt...` → `looksLikeCookingInstruction` matches → j=3\n   348→- j≥3 → skip to line 3\n   349→\n   350→After skipping, `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` is at line 4. But with the corroboration check using `burstEnd=3`, \"carpaccio\", \"pesce\", \"spada\" have no vocabulary support in the Mushroom Risotto content later in the file. The existing corroboration logic (already passing `burstEnd` from iteration 28) should now filter it out.\n   351→\n   352→If `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` still survives (e.g., corroboration is too lenient), a supplementary check: when `isTitleAbsentPage` would have been true for lines 0..burstEnd (all instructions/prose), apply extra skepticism to ALL_CAPS titles in the early post-burst region that have zero vocabulary overlap with the document body after the first structural gap (2+ blank lines).\n   353→\n   354→**Risk:** The unified body-content check is more permissive — it could skip past a legitimate title that follows 3 lines of prose (e.g., a recipe that opens with a description). Mitigated by: (1) the prose check requires lowercase-start, which excludes title-case and ALL_CAPS titles; (2) the threshold is still 3 consecutive lines; (3) titles typically don't follow 3+ lines of body prose without a blank line or heading.\n   355→\n   356→---\n   357→\n   358→## Implementation Order\n   359→\n   360→1. **Fix 1: Dual-variant OCR repair** — Highest impact (6 cases). Fixes the root cause of the largest failure cluster. Extract `generateBlindOcrVariants` with both `i` and `l` paths, add erratic-casing normalization.\n   361→\n   362→2. **Fix 2: English category labels in hard filters** — Simple one-line addition plus a few new entries. Enables Fix 3 to work. Low regression risk.\n   363→\n   364→3. **Fix 3: Direct-successor blank-line skip** — Small change to existing bonus logic. Depends on Fix 2 for `isCategorySectionLabel` checks.\n   365→\n   366→4. **Fix 4: Overflow marker regex** — Simple regex broadening. Isolated from other changes.\n   367→\n   368→5. **Fix 5: Unified body-content prologue** — Highest regression risk. Changes `findBurstEnd` behavior for all files. Run full eval after this change specifically.\n   369→\n   370→## Testing Strategy\n   371→\n   372→- Run the full eval suite after each fix (using `eval_only.py`)\n   373→- After Fix 1: expect Braised Cod, Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami, Roasted Beet, Żurek Krakowski, Kopytka to pass\n   374→- After Fix 2+3: expect Halibut, Roasted Asparagus, Ogórkowa Zupa to pass\n   375→- After Fix 4: expect Peach Cobbler to pass\n   376→- After Fix 5: expect Mushroom Risotto to pass\n   377→- Watch for regressions especially in: multi-recipe pages (Fix 5 changes burst detection), ALL_CAPS titles (Fix 2 filters more aggressively), compound titles (Fix 2's `&` detection)\n   378→\n   379→## Files to Modify\n   380→\n   381→- `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts` — all 5 fixes\n   382→\n   383→## Open Questions\n   384→\n   385→1. **Fix 1 variant count:** Should we cap the total number of OCR variants per line at 2 (one `i`, one `l`), or also generate a mixed variant where each `1` is resolved independently based on surrounding vowel/consonant context? Two variants is simpler and should suffice — the embedding scorer picks the better one.\n   386→\n   387→2. **Fix 2 completeness:** The `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` set may be incomplete for English. Should we add more categories like `\"sides\"`, `\"starters\"`, `\"mains\"`, `\"entrees\"`, `\"beverages\"`, `\"sauces\"`, `\"dips\"`, `\"condiments\"`? Adding more is safe — single-word ALL_CAPS food categories are almost never recipe titles.\n   388→\n   389→3. **Fix 5 interaction with `isTitleAbsentPage`:** After the unified body-content prologue skip, `isTitleAbsentPage` may also fire (it checks the original first 3 lines, not post-burst lines). If both fire, the extractor returns empty — which is the correct behavior when the page genuinely starts mid-recipe. But if the burst skip advances past the prologue and a real title exists post-burst, `isTitleAbsentPage` shouldn't prevent extraction. Verify that `isTitleAbsentPage` is checked BEFORE `findBurstEnd` is applied, or that it checks only the relevant region.\n   390→\n   391→## References\n   392→\n   393→- Iteration 28 feedback: `tools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/feedback.md`\n   394→- Iteration 27 plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md`\n   395→- Previous iteration history: `tools/title-loop/docs/iter.txt`\n   396→- Test fixtures: `tools/title-loop/input/*.generated.txt`\n   397→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7a8a1052-f060-407b-8164-bf7c5f97f8a0","uuid":"d3aa690d-1ac5-4c97-af6a-b35ee0db2faa","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md","content":"# Iteration 29 — Improvement Plan\n\n**Status:** Draft\n**Date:** 2026-03-17\n**Based on:** Iteration 28 feedback (11 failures, all generated files)\n\n## Overview\n\nIteration 28 implemented all 4 fixes from the iteration 27 plan (blind OCR repair, direct-successor bonus, multi-line dedup protection, spillover threshold lowering). The score held at 90.1% — the same 11 failures persist. By reading the actual test files and tracing through the code, this plan identifies why each fix failed and proposes corrected approaches.\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nThe iteration 27 plan correctly identified the 4 failure patterns but the implementations had bugs or gaps:\n\n1. **Blind OCR repair maps `1→l` instead of `1→i`** — The mixed-case path in `applyBlindOcrRepair` always substitutes `l`, producing garbled text like `Bralsed Cod wlth Whlte Wlne` instead of `Braised Cod with White Wine`.\n2. **Direct-successor bonus ignores blank lines** — The bonus checks `lines[position - 1]`, but in both the Halibut and Ogórkowa Zupa files, there's a blank line between the header and the title. The bonus never fires.\n3. **English food categories not treated as section labels** — `VEGETABLES` and `FISH & SEAFOOD` pass hard filters because only Polish food categories (warzywa, ryby, etc.) are in `SECTION_LABELS`. English equivalents (vegetables, fish, seafood) are only in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`, which `passesHardFilters` doesn't check.\n4. **Overflow marker regex doesn't match actual test marker** — `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]` fails to match the regex `PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\s+(OVERFLOW|CONTENT)` because the text says `PREVIOUS PAGE` followed by `- PARTIAL RECIPE`, not `OVERFLOW` or `CONTENT`.\n5. **`findBurstEnd` misses non-consecutive instruction prologues** — The Mushroom Risotto file alternates cooking instructions (`Reduce heat...`, `Season with...`) with prose (`creamy but still al dente...`), breaking the consecutive-instruction count at j=1.\n\n## Goals\n\n- Fix the root causes identified above, not just increase bonuses or thresholds\n- Fix all 11 failures without regressing existing passing tests\n- Keep changes targeted — the architecture works, the edge-case handling has specific bugs\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Replacing the embedding-based approach\n- Reducing overall code complexity\n- Handling new patterns not seen in iterations 27-28\n\n---\n\n## Fix 1: Dual-variant blind OCR repair (5 cases + 1 case)\n\n**Affects:** Braised Cod with White Wine, Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami, Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip, Żurek Krakowski, Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi\n\n### Root Cause\n\n`applyBlindOcrRepair` in mixed-case mode has:\n```typescript\n.replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])1/g, \"l\")\n.replace(/1(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"l\")\n```\n\nThis always maps `1→l`. For recipe text, `1→i` is correct far more often:\n- `Bra1sed` → should be `Braised` (i), not `Bralsed` (l)\n- `w1th` → should be `with` (i), not `wlth` (l)\n- `Wh1te` → should be `White` (i), not `Whlte` (l)\n- `W1ne` → should be `Wine` (i), not `Wlne` (l)\n- `Sern1k` → should be `Sernik` (i), not `Sernlk` (l)\n\nThe ALL_CAPS path (`1→I`) works because uppercase `I` and `L` are visually similar and `I` is the correct character for most recipe words. The mixed-case path needs the same correctness.\n\nAdditionally, `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi` has erratic casing (`KoPyTka`) that doesn't trigger the ALL_CAPS path and confuses the mixed-case repair.\n\n### Fix\n\n**Part A: Generate both `i` and `l` variants as separate candidates.**\n\nInstead of choosing one substitution, generate two candidates — one with `1→i` and one with `1→l`. The embedding scorer will pick the one that embeds as a better title. This avoids needing to guess which letter is correct.\n\n```typescript\n// In buildCandidates, replace the single blind-repair block with:\nif (line.index <= 5 && OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text)) {\n  const variants = generateBlindOcrVariants(singleText);\n  for (const variant of variants) {\n    if (variant !== singleText && passesHardFilters(variant)) {\n      const norm = variant.toLowerCase();\n      if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n        seen.add(norm);\n        candidates.push({ text: variant, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n`generateBlindOcrVariants` returns an array of up to 2 variants:\n1. `i`-variant: `1→i` between lowercase letters, `¡→i`, `€→e`\n2. `l`-variant: `1→l` between lowercase letters (the current behavior)\n\nFor ALL_CAPS text, only one variant (`1→I`) is needed (current behavior is correct).\n\n**Part B: Normalize erratic casing before repair.**\n\nFor the Kopytka case (`KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi`), add a casing normalization step that detects erratic mixed-case (neither title-case nor ALL_CAPS) and normalizes to title-case before OCR repair. A line has \"erratic casing\" when individual words have uppercase letters in non-initial positions (like `KoPyTka` where `P`, `T`, `k` break the pattern).\n\n```typescript\nfunction hasErraticCasing(text: string): boolean {\n  return text.split(/\\s+/).some(word => {\n    if (word.length < 3) return false;\n    if (isAllCaps(word)) return false;\n    // Check for uppercase letters after position 0 that aren't part of known patterns\n    // (e.g., McDonald's is OK, KoPyTka is not)\n    const inner = word.slice(1);\n    const upperInner = (inner.match(/[A-ZÀ-Ż]/g) || []).length;\n    const lowerInner = (inner.match(/[a-zà-ż]/g) || []).length;\n    return upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3;\n  });\n}\n\nfunction normalizeErraticCasing(text: string): string {\n  return text.split(/(\\s+)/).map(token => {\n    if (/^\\s+$/.test(token)) return token;\n    if (isAllCaps(token)) return token;\n    if (hasErraticCasing(token)) {\n      // Normalize to title-case: first letter upper, rest lower\n      return token.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + token.slice(1).toLowerCase();\n    }\n    return token;\n  }).join(\"\");\n}\n```\n\nApply this normalization as a pre-step before blind OCR repair for early-position candidates:\n\n```typescript\nif (line.index <= 5 && (OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text) || hasErraticCasing(line.text))) {\n  let repairable = singleText;\n  if (hasErraticCasing(repairable)) {\n    repairable = normalizeErraticCasing(repairable);\n  }\n  const variants = generateBlindOcrVariants(repairable);\n  // ... add variants as candidates\n}\n```\n\n**Why this works:**\n- `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne` → `i`-variant: `Braised Cod with White Wine` (embeds perfectly as a title)\n- `Drożdże Sern1k` → `i`-variant: `Drożdże Sernik` (correct)\n- `KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi` → normalize: `Kopytka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi` → repair `¡→i`: `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi` (correct)\n\n**Risk:** Generating extra candidates costs one additional embedding computation per variant. With the limit of first 5 lines, this adds at most 5 extra candidates — well within the 25-candidate cap. The embedding scorer naturally rejects wrong variants (e.g., `l`-variant `Bralsed` will score poorly).\n\n---\n\n## Fix 2: Add English food categories to hard-filter section labels (3 cases)\n\n**Affects:** Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce, Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan, Ogórkowa Zupa (indirectly)\n\n### Root Cause\n\n`passesHardFilters` calls `isSectionLabel`, which checks `SECTION_LABELS`. Polish food categories (warzywa, mieso, ryby, zupy, etc.) are in `SECTION_LABELS` and get filtered. But their English equivalents are only in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`, which `passesHardFilters` doesn't check.\n\nResult: `VEGETABLES` (from the Roasted Asparagus file) passes hard filters and becomes a candidate with ALL_CAPS bonus. `FISH & SEAFOOD` (from the Halibut file) also passes.\n\n### Fix\n\nAdd `isCategorySectionLabel` as a hard filter check:\n\n```typescript\nfunction passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n  // ... existing checks ...\n  if (isSectionLabel(text)) return false;\n  if (isCategorySectionLabel(text)) return false;  // NEW\n  // ... rest of checks ...\n}\n```\n\nAlso handle compound category headers like `FISH & SEAFOOD`:\n\n```typescript\n// In passesHardFilters, after the isCategorySectionLabel check:\n// Multi-word category headers: \"FISH & SEAFOOD\", \"MEAT & POULTRY\"\nif (/ [&] /.test(text)) {\n  const parts = text.split(/\\s*&\\s*/);\n  if (parts.every(p => isCategorySectionLabel(p.trim()))) return false;\n}\n```\n\nThis needs `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` to also include common header components: add `\"meat\"`, `\"fish & seafood\"`, `\"meat & poultry\"`.\n\n**Why this works:** `VEGETABLES` → `isCategorySectionLabel(\"vegetables\")` → true → filtered. `FISH & SEAFOOD` → split on `&` → `[\"FISH\", \"SEAFOOD\"]` → both in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` → filtered. The actual titles (`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce`, `Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan`) are multi-word recipe names that won't match category labels.\n\n**Risk:** Could filter a legitimate title that's a single food category word (e.g., a recipe literally called \"Vegetables\"). Mitigated by the fact that real recipe titles are almost always more specific (\"Roasted Vegetables\", \"Vegetable Stir Fry\"). Single-word category headers are section labels, not recipe titles.\n\n---\n\n## Fix 3: Direct-successor bonus should skip blank lines (2 cases)\n\n**Affects:** Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce, Ogórkowa Zupa\n\n### Root Cause\n\nThe direct-successor bonus (added in iteration 28) checks `lines[candidate.position - 1]`. In both failing files, there's a blank line between the header and the title:\n\n```\nFISH & SEAFOOD        ← header (line 0)\n                      ← blank (line 1)\nHalibut with ...      ← title (line 2), but lines[2-1] = blank\n```\n\n```\nLato | Zupy | ...     ← metadata (line 0)\n                      ← blank (line 1)\nOGÓRKOWA ZUPA         ← title (line 2), but lines[2-1] = blank\n```\n\nThe bonus never fires because blank lines are not headers.\n\n### Fix\n\nScan backward from the candidate to find the nearest non-empty line, instead of just checking position-1:\n\n```typescript\nfor (let ci = 0; ci < scored.length && ci <= 2; ci++) {\n  const candidate = scored[ci];\n  if (candidate.position > 0) {\n    // Scan backward past blank lines to find nearest non-empty preceding line\n    let prevPos = candidate.position - 1;\n    while (prevPos >= 0 && lines[prevPos].trim() === \"\") {\n      prevPos--;\n    }\n    if (prevPos >= 0) {\n      const prevLine = lines[prevPos].trim();\n      const prevIsHeader =\n        isSectionLabel(prevLine) ||\n        isCategorySectionLabel(prevLine) ||          // NEW: also check category labels\n        looksLikeMetadata(prevLine) ||\n        prevLine.includes(\" | \") ||\n        (/ [&] /.test(prevLine) &&                   // NEW: compound category headers\n         prevLine.split(/\\s*&\\s*/).every(p => isCategorySectionLabel(p.trim())));\n      if (prevIsHeader) {\n        candidate.score += 0.10;\n        candidate.baseScore += 0.10;\n        candidate.thresholdScore += 0.10;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nNote: With Fix 2, `FISH & SEAFOOD` and `VEGETABLES` are now filtered by hard filters and won't be candidates. But they still exist as lines that the direct-successor bonus should detect. The bonus now also checks `isCategorySectionLabel` when scanning previous lines, so it recognizes `FISH & SEAFOOD` / `VEGETABLES` as headers even though they're filtered from candidacy.\n\n**Why this works:** For Halibut, the bonus scans back from position 2, skips blank line 1, finds `FISH & SEAFOOD` at position 0. Compound category check matches. Bonus fires.\n\nFor Ogórkowa Zupa, scans back from position 2, skips blank line 1, finds `Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...` at position 0. `prevLine.includes(\" | \")` matches. Bonus fires.\n\n**Risk:** Scanning too far back could match a stale header. Mitigated by the existing `ci <= 2` guard (only top 3 candidates) and by requiring the previous non-empty line to actually be a header pattern.\n\n---\n\n## Fix 4: Broaden overflow marker detection (1 case)\n\n**Affects:** Peach Cobbler\n\n### Root Cause\n\nThe file starts with `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]`. The `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` regex is:\n```\n/\\b(PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\s+(OVERFLOW|CONTENT)|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION|CORRUPTED\\s+SECTION)\\b/i\n```\n\nThis expects:\n- `PREVIOUS RECIPE OVERFLOW` or `PREVIOUS PAGE OVERFLOW` or `PREVIOUS PAGE CONTENT`\n- `SPILLOVER`\n- `CONTINUATION`\n- `CORRUPTED SECTION`\n\nThe actual text has `CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE` — `CORRUPTED` is not followed by `SECTION`, and `PREVIOUS PAGE` is not followed by `OVERFLOW`/`CONTENT`.\n\n### Fix\n\nBroaden the regex to match more natural variations of corruption/spillover markers:\n\n```typescript\nconst OVERFLOW_MARKERS = /\\b(PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\b|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION|CORRUPTED\\s+(SECTION|TEXT)\\b|PARTIAL\\s+RECIPE)\\b/i;\n```\n\nChanges:\n- `PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)` — no longer requires `OVERFLOW`/`CONTENT` after it. Any mention of \"previous recipe\" or \"previous page\" is an overflow signal.\n- `CORRUPTED\\s+(SECTION|TEXT)` — matches both `CORRUPTED SECTION` and `CORRUPTED TEXT`.\n- `PARTIAL\\s+RECIPE` — matches the `PARTIAL RECIPE` marker directly.\n\nAlso add a check for the common `[...]` bracket pattern used in generated files:\n\n```typescript\n// Additional overflow detection: lines that are fully bracketed annotations\n// like \"[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]\"\nif (/^\\[.*\\b(PREVIOUS|CORRUPTED|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION)\\b.*\\]$/i.test(lines[k].text)) {\n  // Treat as overflow marker — scan forward for boundary\n  // ... same forward-scan logic as existing overflow handling\n}\n```\n\n**Why this works:** `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]` now matches via both `CORRUPTED\\s+TEXT` and `PARTIAL\\s+RECIPE` and the bracketed-annotation check. The forward scan finds the `---` separator at line 20 and sets `overflowEnd` to 21. `PEACH COBBLER` at line 22 is the first candidate after spillover.\n\n**Risk:** Broader matching could trigger on legitimate recipe text that happens to contain words like \"previous\" or \"partial\". Mitigated by requiring the match to be part of a marker phrase (word boundary `\\b` + multi-word patterns), not just a standalone word. The bracketed-annotation check is safe because `[...]` lines are already filtered by hard filters — this just ensures the spillover skip logic also catches them.\n\n---\n\n## Fix 5: Detect interleaved instruction/prose prologues (1 case)\n\n**Affects:** Mushroom Risotto\n\n### Root Cause\n\nThe file starts with:\n```\nReduce heat and stir in the remaining stock, one ladle at a time, until the rice is   ← cooking instruction (Reduce)\ncreamy but still al dente, about 18-20 minutes. The risotto should flow slightly...    ← prose continuation\nSeason with salt and white pepper. Finish with butter and grated Parmigiano-Reggiano.  ← cooking instruction (Season/Finish)\n```\n\n`findBurstEnd`'s instruction-prologue check requires CONSECUTIVE lines matching `looksLikeCookingInstruction`. Line 0 matches (`Reduce`), but line 1 starts with `creamy` (lowercase, no cooking verb), breaking the streak at j=1. The threshold is j≥3, so no skip occurs.\n\nThe prose-prologue check also fails: line 0 starts with uppercase `R`, which doesn't match the lowercase-start requirement.\n\n### Fix\n\nReplace the strict consecutive-instruction/prose checks with a unified \"body-content prologue\" detector that tolerates interleaving. The insight is that spillover text is a mix of instructions and prose — we should count EITHER type:\n\n```typescript\n// In findBurstEnd, replace the separate instruction-prologue and prose-prologue checks with:\nif (i === 0) {\n  let j = 0;\n  while (j < lines.length) {\n    const t = lines[j].text;\n    const isInstruction = looksLikeCookingInstruction(t);\n    const isProse = (\n      /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(t) ||\n      t.endsWith(\",\") ||\n      (t.endsWith(\".\") && wordCount(t) > 4)\n    ) && wordCount(t) >= 4;\n    // Also detect continuation lines: start lowercase or with a comma/conjunction\n    const isContinuation = /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(t) && wordCount(t) >= 2;\n\n    if (isInstruction || isProse || isContinuation) {\n      j++;\n    } else {\n      break;\n    }\n  }\n  if (j >= 3) {\n    i = j;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe key change: instructions and prose lines are counted together. A cooking instruction followed by a prose continuation followed by another instruction all count toward the threshold.\n\n**Why this works:** For Mushroom Risotto:\n- Line 0: `Reduce heat and stir...` → `looksLikeCookingInstruction` matches → j=1\n- Line 1: `creamy but still al dente...` → starts lowercase, 4+ words → `isContinuation` matches → j=2\n- Line 2: `Season with salt...` → `looksLikeCookingInstruction` matches → j=3\n- j≥3 → skip to line 3\n\nAfter skipping, `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` is at line 4. But with the corroboration check using `burstEnd=3`, \"carpaccio\", \"pesce\", \"spada\" have no vocabulary support in the Mushroom Risotto content later in the file. The existing corroboration logic (already passing `burstEnd` from iteration 28) should now filter it out.\n\nIf `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` still survives (e.g., corroboration is too lenient), a supplementary check: when `isTitleAbsentPage` would have been true for lines 0..burstEnd (all instructions/prose), apply extra skepticism to ALL_CAPS titles in the early post-burst region that have zero vocabulary overlap with the document body after the first structural gap (2+ blank lines).\n\n**Risk:** The unified body-content check is more permissive — it could skip past a legitimate title that follows 3 lines of prose (e.g., a recipe that opens with a description). Mitigated by: (1) the prose check requires lowercase-start, which excludes title-case and ALL_CAPS titles; (2) the threshold is still 3 consecutive lines; (3) titles typically don't follow 3+ lines of body prose without a blank line or heading.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Order\n\n1. **Fix 1: Dual-variant OCR repair** — Highest impact (6 cases). Fixes the root cause of the largest failure cluster. Extract `generateBlindOcrVariants` with both `i` and `l` paths, add erratic-casing normalization.\n\n2. **Fix 2: English category labels in hard filters** — Simple one-line addition plus a few new entries. Enables Fix 3 to work. Low regression risk.\n\n3. **Fix 3: Direct-successor blank-line skip** — Small change to existing bonus logic. Depends on Fix 2 for `isCategorySectionLabel` checks.\n\n4. **Fix 4: Overflow marker regex** — Simple regex broadening. Isolated from other changes.\n\n5. **Fix 5: Unified body-content prologue** — Highest regression risk. Changes `findBurstEnd` behavior for all files. Run full eval after this change specifically.\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n- Run the full eval suite after each fix (using `eval_only.py`)\n- After Fix 1: expect Braised Cod, Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami, Roasted Beet, Żurek Krakowski, Kopytka to pass\n- After Fix 2+3: expect Halibut, Roasted Asparagus, Ogórkowa Zupa to pass\n- After Fix 4: expect Peach Cobbler to pass\n- After Fix 5: expect Mushroom Risotto to pass\n- Watch for regressions especially in: multi-recipe pages (Fix 5 changes burst detection), ALL_CAPS titles (Fix 2 filters more aggressively), compound titles (Fix 2's `&` detection)\n\n## Files to Modify\n\n- `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts` — all 5 fixes\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. **Fix 1 variant count:** Should we cap the total number of OCR variants per line at 2 (one `i`, one `l`), or also generate a mixed variant where each `1` is resolved independently based on surrounding vowel/consonant context? Two variants is simpler and should suffice — the embedding scorer picks the better one.\n\n2. **Fix 2 completeness:** The `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` set may be incomplete for English. Should we add more categories like `\"sides\"`, `\"starters\"`, `\"mains\"`, `\"entrees\"`, `\"beverages\"`, `\"sauces\"`, `\"dips\"`, `\"condiments\"`? Adding more is safe — single-word ALL_CAPS food categories are almost never recipe titles.\n\n3. **Fix 5 interaction with `isTitleAbsentPage`:** After the unified body-content prologue skip, `isTitleAbsentPage` may also fire (it checks the original first 3 lines, not post-burst lines). If both fire, the extractor returns empty — which is the correct behavior when the page genuinely starts mid-recipe. But if the burst skip advances past the prologue and a real title exists post-burst, `isTitleAbsentPage` shouldn't prevent extraction. Verify that `isTitleAbsentPage` is checked BEFORE `findBurstEnd` is applied, or that it checks only the relevant region.\n\n## References\n\n- Iteration 28 feedback: `tools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/feedback.md`\n- Iteration 27 plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md`\n- Previous iteration history: `tools/title-loop/docs/iter.txt`\n- Test fixtures: `tools/title-loop/input/*.generated.txt`\n","numLines":397,"startLine":1,"totalLines":397}}}
