{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JbFe7NDmDcDDJphJThrzKw","type":"tool_result","content":"<persisted-output>\nOutput too large (20.7KB). Full output saved to: /Users/eryk.napierala/.claude/projects/-Users-eryk-napierala-Projects-fasola/7a8a1052-f060-407b-8164-bf7c5f97f8a0/tool-results/toolu_01JbFe7NDmDcDDJphJThrzKw.txt\n\nPreview (first 2KB):\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:24:## Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter corruption on title line (5 cases)\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:28:**Root cause:** `repairOcrText` only repairs words found in `FOOD_DICTIONARY`. When a corrupted word like `Bra1sed` or `D1p` has no dictionary match, it passes through unrepaired. The corrupted text then either:\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:33:**Fix: Blind OCR repair for early-position candidates**\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:35:[Omitted long matching line]\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:37:The existing `normalizeOcrTitle` already does blind digit→letter substitution (1→I, 4→A, 5→S, 0→O) but only as post-processing on the *winner*. The fix is to apply the same blind repair *before* embedding, specifically for candidates in the first few lines where positional evidence is strong.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:41:In `buildCandidates`, after constructing each single-line candidate from the first 3 non-empty lines, generate a second \"OCR-repaired\" variant using blind substitution (the same logic as `normalizeOcrTitle` step 2). If the repaired text differs from the original AND passes hard filters, add it as an additional candidate at the same position. This gives the embedding scorer a clean version to work with.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:45:if (line.index <= 5 && OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(singleText)) {\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:46:  const blindRepaired = applyBlindOcrRepair(singleText);\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:47:  if (blindRepaired !== singleText && passesHardFilters(blindRepaired)) {\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:48:    const norm = blindRepaired.toLowerCase();\n...\n</persisted-output>"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7a8a1052-f060-407b-8164-bf7c5f97f8a0","uuid":"0eef1098-ef48-4130-9bfe-97cd8797332d","tool_use_result":{"mode":"content","numFiles":0,"filenames":[],"content":"tools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:24:## Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter corruption on title line (5 cases)\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:28:**Root cause:** `repairOcrText` only repairs words found in `FOOD_DICTIONARY`. When a corrupted word like `Bra1sed` or `D1p` has no dictionary match, it passes through unrepaired. The corrupted text then either:\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:33:**Fix: Blind OCR repair for early-position candidates**\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:35:[Omitted long matching line]\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:37:The existing `normalizeOcrTitle` already does blind digit→letter substitution (1→I, 4→A, 5→S, 0→O) but only as post-processing on the *winner*. The fix is to apply the same blind repair *before* embedding, specifically for candidates in the first few lines where positional evidence is strong.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:41:In `buildCandidates`, after constructing each single-line candidate from the first 3 non-empty lines, generate a second \"OCR-repaired\" variant using blind substitution (the same logic as `normalizeOcrTitle` step 2). If the repaired text differs from the original AND passes hard filters, add it as an additional candidate at the same position. This gives the embedding scorer a clean version to work with.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:45:if (line.index <= 5 && OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(singleText)) {\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:46:  const blindRepaired = applyBlindOcrRepair(singleText);\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:47:  if (blindRepaired !== singleText && passesHardFilters(blindRepaired)) {\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:48:    const norm = blindRepaired.toLowerCase();\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:51:      candidates.push({ text: blindRepaired, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:57:Extract the blind substitution logic from `normalizeOcrTitle` into a reusable `applyBlindOcrRepair` function. This function applies:\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:63:**Why this works:** The true title at line 1 with `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne` becomes `Braised Cod with White Wine` after blind repair. This clean version embeds well and gets a high title similarity score. The original corrupted version also stays in the pool as a fallback. The position bonus for early candidates ensures the repaired version outscores garbage text later in the file.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:65:**Risk:** Blind repair could create false words (e.g., `H1GH` → `HIGH` when the original was a code). Mitigated by limiting to the first 5 lines (title region) and by requiring the repaired text to pass all hard filters.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:81:[Omitted long matching line]\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:83:The first-after-preamble bonus currently checks whether ALL preceding lines were filtered. If any non-filtered line exists before the first candidate, the bonus doesn't fire. The fix: extend the bonus to fire when the *immediately preceding* line (not all preceding lines) was a section label or metadata, regardless of what came before that.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:87:Add a \"direct-successor\" bonus in the scoring pass:\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:91:// Direct successor bonus: if the line immediately before this candidate\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:92:// is a section label, metadata, or pipe-separated line, this candidate\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:96:  const prevIsHeader = isSectionLabel(prevLine) ||\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:109:**Why this works:** For `FISH & SEAFOOD\\nHalibut with Saffron Cream Sauce`, the header is filtered, and \"Halibut...\" is the first candidate. It gets both the existing first-after-preamble bonus AND the direct-successor bonus, making it decisively outscore description text later in the file.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:111:For `Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...\\nOgórkowa Zupa`, the pipe line is filtered, and \"Ogórkowa Zupa\" immediately follows and gets the direct-successor bonus.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:123:The caps coalescing logic in `buildCandidates` likely already merges `LEMON HERB RO45TED` + `VEGETABLES` into a single candidate. After OCR repair, both `LEMON HERB ROASTED` (single) and `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES` (coalesced or 2-line join) enter the candidate pool. But dedup prefers the shorter one.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:129:In the dedup step, when the longer candidate is a multi-line join (origin `\"2-line\"` or coalesced) and the shorter is its prefix, check if the suffix word(s) are food-related (in `FOOD_DICTIONARY` or `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`). If so, prefer the longer form — it's a complete title, not an accidental substring match.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:150:      if (CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS.has(suffixNorm) ||\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:162:**Why this works:** `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES` is a 2-line join. Its suffix `VEGETABLES` is in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`. The dedup rule now keeps the longer form.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:172:[Omitted long matching line]\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:174:The existing `isTitleAbsentPage` check (requires first 3 non-empty lines to be ingredients/instructions/prose) should catch many of these cases. The feedback says it returns `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` for Mushroom Risotto — this is a different recipe's ALL_CAPS title in the spillover. The title-absent guard filters by `rawScore >= 0.10` and `position <= 2`, but the foreign recipe title may be at a low position and have a good rawScore.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:176:**Fix: Extend spillover detection and corroboration**\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:180:1. **Broaden `findBurstEnd` to detect implicit spillover:** When the first 3+ non-empty lines are a mix of ingredients, instructions, and body prose (not preceded by any title-shaped line), and then a blank-line gap or visual separator appears, skip past it. This is already partially handled by `isTitleAbsentPage` and the prose-prologue skip in `findBurstEnd`.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:182:[Omitted long matching line]\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:184:[Omitted long matching line]\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:189:// In findBurstEnd: lower the cooking-instruction prologue threshold\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:209:Then in the multi-title guard, pass `burstEnd` as `startLine` so that vocabulary from the spillover region doesn't count as corroboration for a spillover recipe title.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:211:**Why this works:** `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` has no vocabulary support in the Mushroom Risotto recipe body (no mention of \"carpaccio\", \"pesce\", or \"spada\"). With corroboration checking only the post-spillover region, it gets filtered. `MUSHROOM RISOTTO` (if it appears as a candidate) has vocabulary support (\"mushroom\" in ingredients, \"risotto\" in instructions).\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:213:**Risk:** Lowering the instruction-prologue threshold from 5 to 3 could skip legitimate title regions that happen to start with 3 instruction-like lines. Mitigated by the fact that the skip only fires when ALL of the first lines match instruction patterns — a title mixed in would break the streak.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:219:1. **Pattern 1 (OCR blind repair)** — Highest impact (5 cases). Extract `applyBlindOcrRepair` from `normalizeOcrTitle`, call it in `buildCandidates` for early-position candidates.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:225:4. **Pattern 4 (spillover detection)** — Highest regression risk (2 cases). Changes to `findBurstEnd` and corroboration affect all test cases. Run full eval after each sub-change.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:231:- Watch for regressions in the corresponding pattern category (e.g., OCR repair changes could affect other OCR cases)\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:241:1. **Pattern 1 scope:** Should blind OCR repair apply to ALL candidates or only the first N lines? First 5 lines is proposed but could be tuned. The dictionary-guided repair (iterations 24-26) continues to run for all candidates regardless.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:242:2. **Pattern 2 bonus stacking:** The direct-successor bonus stacks with the first-after-preamble bonus, but the existing `maxPositionalBoost` cap (0.15) limits the total. This is consistent with iteration 26's design.\ntools/title-loop/docs/27-51f970e/improvement-plan.md:243:3. **Pattern 4 threshold:** Is lowering instruction-prologue skip from 5→3 too aggressive? Iteration 21 chose 5 deliberately to avoid skipping legitimate recipe openings. Iteration 26's improved post-skip structural detection mitigates this risk. Try 3 first; fall back to 4 if regressions appear.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:9:Iteration 28 implemented all 4 fixes from the iteration 27 plan (blind OCR repair, direct-successor bonus, multi-line dedup protection, spillover threshold lowering). The score held at 90.1% — the same 11 failures persist. By reading the actual test files and tracing through the code, this plan identifies why each fix failed and proposes corrected approaches.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:15:1. **Blind OCR repair maps `1→l` instead of `1→i`** — The mixed-case path in `applyBlindOcrRepair` always substitutes `l`, producing garbled text like `Bralsed Cod wlth Whlte Wlne` instead of `Braised Cod with White Wine`.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:16:2. **Direct-successor bonus ignores blank lines** — The bonus checks `lines[position - 1]`, but in both the Halibut and Ogórkowa Zupa files, there's a blank line between the header and the title. The bonus never fires.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:17:3. **English food categories not treated as section labels** — `VEGETABLES` and `FISH & SEAFOOD` pass hard filters because only Polish food categories (warzywa, ryby, etc.) are in `SECTION_LABELS`. English equivalents (vegetables, fish, seafood) are only in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`, which `passesHardFilters` doesn't check.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:18:4. **Overflow marker regex doesn't match actual test marker** — `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]` fails to match the regex `PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\s+(OVERFLOW|CONTENT)` because the text says `PREVIOUS PAGE` followed by `- PARTIAL RECIPE`, not `OVERFLOW` or `CONTENT`.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:19:5. **`findBurstEnd` misses non-consecutive instruction prologues** — The Mushroom Risotto file alternates cooking instructions (`Reduce heat...`, `Season with...`) with prose (`creamy but still al dente...`), breaking the consecutive-instruction count at j=1.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:35:## Fix 1: Dual-variant blind OCR repair (5 cases + 1 case)\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:41:`applyBlindOcrRepair` in mixed-case mode has:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:47:This always maps `1→l`. For recipe text, `1→i` is correct far more often:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:54:The ALL_CAPS path (`1→I`) works because uppercase `I` and `L` are visually similar and `I` is the correct character for most recipe words. The mixed-case path needs the same correctness.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:62:Instead of choosing one substitution, generate two candidates — one with `1→i` and one with `1→l`. The embedding scorer will pick the one that embeds as a better title. This avoids needing to guess which letter is correct.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:65:// In buildCandidates, replace the single blind-repair block with:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:66:if (line.index <= 5 && OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text)) {\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:67:  const variants = generateBlindOcrVariants(singleText);\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:80:`generateBlindOcrVariants` returns an array of up to 2 variants:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:81:1. `i`-variant: `1→i` between lowercase letters, `¡→i`, `€→e`\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:82:2. `l`-variant: `1→l` between lowercase letters (the current behavior)\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:84:For ALL_CAPS text, only one variant (`1→I`) is needed (current behavior is correct).\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:88:For the Kopytka case (`KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi`), add a casing normalization step that detects erratic mixed-case (neither title-case nor ALL_CAPS) and normalizes to title-case before OCR repair. A line has \"erratic casing\" when individual words have uppercase letters in non-initial positions (like `KoPyTka` where `P`, `T`, `k` break the pattern).\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:117:Apply this normalization as a pre-step before blind OCR repair for early-position candidates:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:120:if (line.index <= 5 && (OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text) || hasErraticCasing(line.text))) {\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:125:  const variants = generateBlindOcrVariants(repairable);\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:139:## Fix 2: Add English food categories to hard-filter section labels (3 cases)\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:145:`passesHardFilters` calls `isSectionLabel`, which checks `SECTION_LABELS`. Polish food categories (warzywa, mieso, ryby, zupy, etc.) are in `SECTION_LABELS` and get filtered. But their English equivalents are only in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`, which `passesHardFilters` doesn't check.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:151:Add `isCategorySectionLabel` as a hard filter check:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:156:  if (isSectionLabel(text)) return false;\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:157:  if (isCategorySectionLabel(text)) return false;  // NEW\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:165:// In passesHardFilters, after the isCategorySectionLabel check:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:169:  if (parts.every(p => isCategorySectionLabel(p.trim()))) return false;\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:173:This needs `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` to also include common header components: add `\"meat\"`, `\"fish & seafood\"`, `\"meat & poultry\"`.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:175:**Why this works:** `VEGETABLES` → `isCategorySectionLabel(\"vegetables\")` → true → filtered. `FISH & SEAFOOD` → split on `&` → `[\"FISH\", \"SEAFOOD\"]` → both in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` → filtered. The actual titles (`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce`, `Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan`) are multi-word recipe names that won't match category labels.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:177:**Risk:** Could filter a legitimate title that's a single food category word (e.g., a recipe literally called \"Vegetables\"). Mitigated by the fact that real recipe titles are almost always more specific (\"Roasted Vegetables\", \"Vegetable Stir Fry\"). Single-word category headers are section labels, not recipe titles.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:181:## Fix 3: Direct-successor bonus should skip blank lines (2 cases)\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:187:The direct-successor bonus (added in iteration 28) checks `lines[candidate.position - 1]`. In both failing files, there's a blank line between the header and the title:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:219:        isSectionLabel(prevLine) ||\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:220:        isCategorySectionLabel(prevLine) ||          // NEW: also check category labels\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:224:         prevLine.split(/\\s*&\\s*/).every(p => isCategorySectionLabel(p.trim())));\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:235:Note: With Fix 2, `FISH & SEAFOOD` and `VEGETABLES` are now filtered by hard filters and won't be candidates. But they still exist as lines that the direct-successor bonus should detect. The bonus now also checks `isCategorySectionLabel` when scanning previous lines, so it recognizes `FISH & SEAFOOD` / `VEGETABLES` as headers even though they're filtered from candidacy.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:245:## Fix 4: Broaden overflow marker detection (1 case)\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:251:The file starts with `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]`. The `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` regex is:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:253:/\\b(PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\s+(OVERFLOW|CONTENT)|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION|CORRUPTED\\s+SECTION)\\b/i\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:257:- `PREVIOUS RECIPE OVERFLOW` or `PREVIOUS PAGE OVERFLOW` or `PREVIOUS PAGE CONTENT`\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:258:- `SPILLOVER`\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:262:The actual text has `CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE` — `CORRUPTED` is not followed by `SECTION`, and `PREVIOUS PAGE` is not followed by `OVERFLOW`/`CONTENT`.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:266:Broaden the regex to match more natural variations of corruption/spillover markers:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:269:const OVERFLOW_MARKERS = /\\b(PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\b|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION|CORRUPTED\\s+(SECTION|TEXT)\\b|PARTIAL\\s+RECIPE)\\b/i;\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:273:- `PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)` — no longer requires `OVERFLOW`/`CONTENT` after it. Any mention of \"previous recipe\" or \"previous page\" is an overflow signal.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:280:// Additional overflow detection: lines that are fully bracketed annotations\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:282:if (/^\\[.*\\b(PREVIOUS|CORRUPTED|SPILLOVER|CONTINUATION)\\b.*\\]$/i.test(lines[k].text)) {\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:283:  // Treat as overflow marker — scan forward for boundary\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:284:  // ... same forward-scan logic as existing overflow handling\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:288:**Why this works:** `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]` now matches via both `CORRUPTED\\s+TEXT` and `PARTIAL\\s+RECIPE` and the bracketed-annotation check. The forward scan finds the `---` separator at line 20 and sets `overflowEnd` to 21. `PEACH COBBLER` at line 22 is the first candidate after spillover.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:290:**Risk:** Broader matching could trigger on legitimate recipe text that happens to contain words like \"previous\" or \"partial\". Mitigated by requiring the match to be part of a marker phrase (word boundary `\\b` + multi-word patterns), not just a standalone word. The bracketed-annotation check is safe because `[...]` lines are already filtered by hard filters — this just ensures the spillover skip logic also catches them.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:294:## Fix 5: Detect interleaved instruction/prose prologues (1 case)\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:307:`findBurstEnd`'s instruction-prologue check requires CONSECUTIVE lines matching `looksLikeCookingInstruction`. Line 0 matches (`Reduce`), but line 1 starts with `creamy` (lowercase, no cooking verb), breaking the streak at j=1. The threshold is j≥3, so no skip occurs.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:309:The prose-prologue check also fails: line 0 starts with uppercase `R`, which doesn't match the lowercase-start requirement.\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:313:Replace the strict consecutive-instruction/prose checks with a unified \"body-content prologue\" detector that tolerates interleaving. The insight is that spillover text is a mix of instructions and prose — we should count EITHER type:\ntools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md:316:// In findBurstEnd, replace the separate instruction-prologue and prose-prologue checks with:","numLines":100,"appliedLimit":100}}
