{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014LQo2VTfFEKaFVZmRSa48a","type":"tool_result","content":"tools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:61:The file starts with the *end of a previous recipe* — running body text with verbs, instructions, and no title-like line near position 0. The actual title appears 10-25 lines in. Current `findBurstEnd` only detects:\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:63:- 5+ consecutive cooking instruction lines\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:95:Enhance `findBurstEnd` to detect mid-sentence prose prologues. A sequence of 5+ lines where the majority:\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:101:// After existing burst detection, add prose-prologue detection:\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:116:  if (j >= 3) i = j;  // Lower threshold than cooking instructions (3 vs 5)\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:245:`BARSZCZ` (line 1) is eaten by `findBurstEnd` because `isLikelyGarbled(\"BARSZCZ\")` returns true:\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:248:- Threshold is 15% → **flagged as garbled**\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:267:The burst detector is designed to skip OCR garbage at the start of a file. ALL_CAPS lines are almost always intentional headings, not OCR noise. Modify `findBurstEnd`:\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:270:function findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:429:| 7 | C2 — prose prologue detection | 2 | Low | Medium |\ntools/title-loop/docs/19-55b161b/improvement-plan.md:53:The English cooking-instruction filter was added in iter 19 (Change 5 from the iter 18 plan) and works well for English garbage prologues. The same principle applies to Polish cooking instructions: they start with imperative verbs and are multi-word sentences. No recipe title starts with `Podawaj` (serve), `Dodaj` (add), `Smaż` (fry), or `Gotuj` (cook) followed by 3+ more words.\ntools/title-loop/docs/22-480d364/improvement-plan.md:183:Extend `findBurstEnd` to detect and skip overflow preambles:\ntools/title-loop/docs/22-480d364/improvement-plan.md:186:// In findBurstEnd, add a new check at the start:\ntools/title-loop/docs/22-480d364/improvement-plan.md:475:**C. For Mushroom Risotto specifically:** The file starts with continuation text from a previous recipe. The `findBurstEnd` prose-prologue detection should catch lines 1-3 (which are body text starting with lowercase/ending with periods). Once the overflow is skipped, the actual recipe content starts much later. This case may actually be Pattern 3 (overflow) rather than Pattern 7.\ntools/title-loop/docs/22-480d364/improvement-plan.md:546:| 5 | **Change 3: Overflow detection** | `title-extractor.ts` (findBurstEnd) | None |\ntools/title-loop/docs/23-6e2e2a7/improvement-plan.md:100:const rawScoreThreshold = fallback[0].position <= 2 ? -0.05 : 0.02;\ntools/title-loop/docs/18-1d256ae/improvement-plan.md:218:`findBurstEnd` only skips lines that are BOTH short (< 20 chars) AND garbled. The generated test files have 28–35 lines of long (30–55 char) OCR garbage that look like cooking instructions (`Beat egg whites until stiff peaks form, then fold`). These pass all hard filters and pollute the candidate pool.\ntools/title-loop/docs/18-1d256ae/improvement-plan.md:222:Replace the simplistic `findBurstEnd` with a **content-aware garbage prologue detector**. The key insight: these garbage lines are *cooking instruction fragments* — imperative sentences with cooking verbs. Real recipe titles never contain imperative cooking verbs.\ntools/title-loop/docs/18-1d256ae/improvement-plan.md:250:#### Prong 2: Enhanced `findBurstEnd` with repetition detection\ntools/title-loop/docs/18-1d256ae/improvement-plan.md:255:function findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\ntools/title-loop/docs/18-1d256ae/improvement-plan.md:261:  // New: skip long instruction-like prologues\ntools/title-loop/docs/18-1d256ae/improvement-plan.md:270:      i = j; // Skip the entire instruction prologue\n\n[Showing results with pagination = limit: 40, offset: 0]"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7a8a1052-f060-407b-8164-bf7c5f97f8a0","uuid":"463390d1-ed25-41a7-9bfd-f033ab8230d7","tool_use_result":{"mode":"content","numFiles":0,"filenames":[],"content":"tools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:61:The file starts with the *end of a previous recipe* — running body text with verbs, instructions, and no title-like line near position 0. The actual title appears 10-25 lines in. Current `findBurstEnd` only detects:\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:63:- 5+ consecutive cooking instruction lines\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:95:Enhance `findBurstEnd` to detect mid-sentence prose prologues. A sequence of 5+ lines where the majority:\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:101:// After existing burst detection, add prose-prologue detection:\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:116:  if (j >= 3) i = j;  // Lower threshold than cooking instructions (3 vs 5)\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:245:`BARSZCZ` (line 1) is eaten by `findBurstEnd` because `isLikelyGarbled(\"BARSZCZ\")` returns true:\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:248:- Threshold is 15% → **flagged as garbled**\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:267:The burst detector is designed to skip OCR garbage at the start of a file. ALL_CAPS lines are almost always intentional headings, not OCR noise. Modify `findBurstEnd`:\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:270:function findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\ntools/title-loop/docs/21-f1e3c51/improvement-plan.md:429:| 7 | C2 — prose prologue detection | 2 | Low | Medium |\ntools/title-loop/docs/19-55b161b/improvement-plan.md:5